2026-05-03 | Frequency of Element in Range Queries

Question
Return answers for all queries.
	Key Insight
Instead of scanning every range:
		store all occurrence indices
		of each value.
Example:
		arr = [1,2,1,3,1]
		1 → [0,2,4]
		2 → [1]
		3 → [3]
For query [l,r,x]:
		find indices of x inside [l,r]
using:
		lower_bound(l)
		upper_bound(r)
The difference gives frequency.
	Approach
1.	Create hashmap:
		value → list of indices
2.	Traverse array and store positions.
3.	For each query:
		get occurrence list of x
4.	Use:
		lower_bound(list, l)
		upper_bound(list, r)
5.	Frequency =
		rightPos - leftPos
6.	Store answer.
	Time Complexity
	Preprocessing: O(n)
	Per Query:
		O(log n)
	Total:
		O(n + q log n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> queryResults(vector<int>& arr,
                             vector<vector<int>>& queries) {
        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> pos;
        for(int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            pos[arr[i]].push_back(i);
        }
        vector<int> ans;
        for(auto &q : queries) {
            int l = q[0];
            int r = q[1];
            int x = q[2];
            if(!pos.count(x)) {
                ans.push_back(0);
                continue;
            }
            auto &v = pos[x];
            int left =
                lower_bound(v.begin(),
                            v.end(),
                            l) - v.begin();
            int right =
                upper_bound(v.begin(),
                            v.end(),
                            r) - v.begin();
            ans.push_back(right - left);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
By storing all positions of each value, a range-frequency query becomes:
		"How many stored indices lie in [l, r]?"
This can be answered efficiently using binary search on the occurrence list instead of scanning the entire range.
